01:15.253 --> 01:18.589
Well, what are you
so happy about?

01:18.623 --> 01:19.623
I made bubble-wrap slippers
this morning

01:19.641 --> 01:21.642
while you were in the shower.

01:21.676 --> 01:23.010
I specifically told you
the bubble wrap

01:23.061 --> 01:24.478
is for the dishes.

01:24.512 --> 01:25.729
I also made a hat.

01:25.763 --> 01:26.963
Okay, I'm moving in
with a ten-year-old.

01:26.981 --> 01:28.465
And you love me.

01:28.483 --> 01:29.850
I do.

01:29.901 --> 01:30.934
Hey, I was thinking,

01:30.968 --> 01:31.935
what are we going to do
about our bed?

01:31.969 --> 01:33.020
We already have two.

01:33.071 --> 01:34.488
I know,
but, yeah, we do.

01:34.522 --> 01:37.241
But don't you think a new
beginning deserves a new bed?

01:38.809 --> 01:42.279
That...is incredibly sweet.

01:42.313 --> 01:44.781
Yeah, not bad
for a ten-year-old, huh?

01:44.815 --> 01:46.333
What kind of bed
were you thinking?

01:46.367 --> 01:49.670
Whichever one we pick out
after we test them tonight.

01:49.704 --> 01:52.873
And did you have
any particular test in mind?

01:52.924 --> 01:54.324
Well, now I do.

01:54.342 --> 01:55.325
See, I don't think
the store is

01:55.343 --> 01:56.593
gonna let us run
that kind of test.

01:56.628 --> 01:58.011
Yeah.
No, you're right.

01:58.046 --> 02:00.130
We should probably just test
ours before we go out tonight.

02:00.164 --> 02:03.166
Oh.

02:03.184 --> 02:04.935
What are you doing?

02:04.969 --> 02:07.437
I think that Louis
might have just seen us.

02:07.472 --> 02:08.689
Come on,
what's the difference?

02:08.723 --> 02:10.056
We're moving in together.

02:10.108 --> 02:11.608
I think it's time
we stopped keeping it a secret.

02:11.643 --> 02:13.977
But keeping it a secret
is sort of fun.

02:14.011 --> 02:16.063
- Mm-hmm.
- And sexy.

02:16.114 --> 02:17.364
And I am pro sexy--
I mean, I did make

02:17.398 --> 02:19.366
those bubble-wrap slippers
and hat after all,

02:19.400 --> 02:21.034
which is funny, 'cause...

02:21.069 --> 02:23.153
That's not sexy,
it's just fun.

02:23.187 --> 02:25.989
- It's something.
- Something.

02:26.023 --> 02:28.358
- Something.
- I made you some too.

02:36.334 --> 02:38.752
Hey, Harvey, she won't be back
for another week,

02:38.803 --> 02:40.370
so I don't think you need
to start drinking just yet.

02:40.388 --> 02:41.672
You want to make fun,
or you want to help me

02:41.706 --> 02:43.590
figure out
where to put this?

02:43.641 --> 02:44.925
A bottle of scotch?

02:44.976 --> 02:46.843
You couldn't get her
anything more personal?

02:46.877 --> 02:49.096
- She likes scotch.
- <i>You</i> like scotch.

02:49.147 --> 02:50.480
She likes me.
Therefore...

02:50.515 --> 02:52.149
Why don't you just attach
a card that says,

02:52.183 --> 02:54.551
"Welcome,
generic senior partner"?

02:54.569 --> 02:56.903
This is a $12,000 bottle
of scotch,

02:56.938 --> 02:59.389
and this is one of three
left in the world.

02:59.407 --> 03:01.224
That doesn't say generic,
that says--

03:01.242 --> 03:02.743
You're one
of three very expensive things

03:02.777 --> 03:03.910
I recently purchased.

03:03.945 --> 03:05.895
We worked it out
about the buy-in.

03:05.913 --> 03:06.997
And this is gonna
un-work it out.

03:07.031 --> 03:08.248
You know, it's funny.

03:08.282 --> 03:10.400
First it was too generic.
Now it's special.

03:10.418 --> 03:11.835
What are you saying?

03:11.869 --> 03:13.203
I don't think you have a
problem with my choice of gift.

03:13.237 --> 03:15.756
I think you have a problem
with my choice of recipient.

03:15.790 --> 03:17.741
Do you think Scottie
would even be here

03:17.759 --> 03:18.742
if it wasn't for me?

03:18.760 --> 03:21.211
No, I don't.

03:21.245 --> 03:22.796
Harvey, I want this for you.

03:22.847 --> 03:26.266
I want it to work,
and I'm just trying to--

03:26.300 --> 03:27.584
Make sure
I don't screw it up.

03:27.602 --> 03:29.219
Well, we both know
you're gonna screw it up.

03:29.253 --> 03:32.139
I'm just trying to delay that
as long as possible.

03:33.424 --> 03:35.425
You sure about this?

03:35.443 --> 03:37.561
That bottle is the reason
I buy my own present

03:37.595 --> 03:38.945
for secretary's day.

03:38.980 --> 03:40.697
- There's a secretary's day?
- There is.

03:40.732 --> 03:43.033
And you're very generous.

03:48.706 --> 03:50.073
How you doing, Mike?

03:50.107 --> 03:53.410
Are you excited or what?

03:53.444 --> 03:55.328
Excited about what?

03:55.380 --> 03:56.613
Didn't you get my email?

03:56.631 --> 03:58.165
Oh, there it is.

03:58.216 --> 03:59.416
Why don't you read it?

03:59.450 --> 04:00.550
Oh, actually, you know what,
never mind.

04:00.585 --> 04:02.118
I'll just let you know
what it says.

04:02.136 --> 04:03.336
It's so great.

04:03.388 --> 04:05.222
You're gonna love it.

04:05.256 --> 04:10.177
It says
I invited Henry Gerard here

04:10.228 --> 04:11.895
to give a lecture
this Friday.

04:11.929 --> 04:13.730
That's great.

04:13.765 --> 04:17.651
You don't even know
who he is, do you?

04:17.685 --> 04:19.435
Professor Henry Gerard,

04:19.470 --> 04:21.822
author of the definitive text
in legal ethics

04:21.856 --> 04:24.191
and chair of the department
for the last 20 years.

04:24.242 --> 04:25.809
Yeah, I know who he is.

04:25.827 --> 04:29.529
And do you also remember
what you got in his class?

04:29.580 --> 04:30.781
It's pretty hard to forget
an A-plus.

04:30.815 --> 04:32.315
Yeah, it's pretty hard
to forget a grade

04:32.333 --> 04:34.584
that never happened.

04:34.619 --> 04:39.172
No one gets an A-plus
in Gerard's class.

04:43.628 --> 04:45.178
Yeah, well, no one can recite
an entire chapter

04:45.213 --> 04:46.263
of his book from memory.

04:46.297 --> 04:48.765
But I can and did.
Bullshit-.

04:48.800 --> 04:51.184
You never got an A-plus because
you never took his class.

04:51.219 --> 04:53.854
It's a required class, Louis.
Of course I took it.

04:53.888 --> 04:54.971
Not if you never went
to Harvard.

04:55.005 --> 04:56.005
Louis, that is insane.

04:56.023 --> 04:57.390
I have a transcript
from Harvard.

04:57.442 --> 04:59.142
I have a degree from Harvard.
That's because I--

04:59.176 --> 05:04.064
Wait, let me guess.
'Cause you went to Harvard?

05:04.115 --> 05:07.701
See, Mike,
here's the situation.

05:07.735 --> 05:10.570
I don't believe you.

05:10.621 --> 05:12.989
And I don't want to call
Gerard up and ask him

05:13.023 --> 05:15.859
'cause I don't want
the world laughing at my firm.

05:15.877 --> 05:17.694
But if he doesn't walk up
to you on Friday

05:17.712 --> 05:21.030
and say, "Mike Ross,
my beloved student

05:21.048 --> 05:23.133
"who I remember,
because he's the only one

05:23.167 --> 05:24.634
I ever gave an A-plus to,"

05:24.669 --> 05:27.671
well, then, I'm gonna know
you're lying.

05:27.705 --> 05:28.722
And if you still
don't come clean,

05:28.756 --> 05:30.557
I'm gonna launch
a formal investigation,

05:30.591 --> 05:32.709
whether it makes my firm
look bad or not.

05:32.727 --> 05:34.878
This is crazy.
There is nothing to investigate.

05:34.896 --> 05:37.731
Well, I'd rather risk looking
crazy to root out an impostor

05:37.765 --> 05:40.350
than to risk letting
that impostor poison everything

05:40.384 --> 05:42.719
that I stand for.

05:42.737 --> 05:45.405
It's over, Mike.

05:45.439 --> 05:47.741
I'm on to you,

05:47.775 --> 05:49.326
and I'm gonna expose you

05:49.360 --> 05:53.363
for the lying piece of filth
that you are.

05:55.116 --> 05:56.283
Don't forget to rinse
your mouth out

05:56.334 --> 06:00.003
after you're done
throwing up.

